    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Making Music Without the Chancellor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Peggy Sweeney letter on Isaac Stern giving violin lesson to New York City school superintendents scores poor grammar of one superintendent quoted in May 11 article</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I grinned with delight when I read your May 11 news article about Isaac Stern's violin lesson for New York City school superintendents, but the grin turned to groan when I reached the comment from the superintendent who said, ''I thought I did pretty good.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I grinned with delight when I read your May 11 news article about Isaac Stern's violin lesson for New York City school superintendents, but the grin turned to groan when I reached the comment from the superintendent who said, ''I thought I did pretty good.''</p>
        <p>If school superintendents cannot speak English properly, what hope do we have for our children?</p>
        <p>PEGGY SWEENEY  Sarasota, Fla., May 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
